<subSubSection lastPageId="346" lastPageNumber="347" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" type="note">
<paragraph pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="345" pageNumber="346">
Two other subspecies, one from Morocco (
<taxonomicName class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="curtum" subSpecies="moroccanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Asaphidion curtum moroccanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Antoine) and the other from the Canary Islands (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Uyttenboogaart" authorityYear="1928" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="345" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="curtum" subSpecies="delatorrei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="345" pageNumber="346">Asaphidion curtum delatorrei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Uyttenboogaart), are recognized.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/30923" pageId="346" pageNumber="347" start="Figure 22" startId="F22">
<paragraph pageId="346" pageNumber="347">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="346" pageNumber="347">
<pageBreakToken pageId="346" pageNumber="347" start="start">Figure</pageBreakToken>
22.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="curtum" authorityName="curtum (Heyden" authorityYear="1870" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="346" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="curtum" subSpecies="curtum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="346" pageNumber="347">Asaphidion curtum curtum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Heyden). This adventive bembidiine was reported in the North American literature under the name 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1760" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="346" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="346" pageNumber="347">Asaphidion flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Linnaeus) until a study of the male genitalia showed that the specimens were in fact conspecific with the morphologically similar 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Heyden" baseAuthorityYear="1870" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="346" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curtum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="346" pageNumber="347">Asaphidion curtum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="des Gozis" authorityYear="1886" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Asaphidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="346" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="346" pageNumber="347">Asaphidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are odd-looking bembidiines and Linnaeus originally associated them with tiger beetles probably because of their large eyes and absence of elytral striae.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
